<LENGTH>
<P>
804 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALICE KAHN: A BIRTHDAY PARTY TAKES THE CAKE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Alice Kahn 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Like a mythic figure somewhere between Mother Goose and the Good Witch of the 
North, Dear Abby came for us. "What should I call you?" asked my 10-year-old 
daughter, Hannah. "Should I call you Abby or Dear?" 
</P>
<P>
"Call me Abby, honey," said Pauline Esther (Popo) Friedman Phillips, a.k.a. 
Abigail Van Buren. She sat not in a golden coach or a pumpkin shell but in a 
huge white stretch limo with smoked-glass windows and a bar and a phone and a 
television set and a VCR. 
</P>
<P>
"This is so cool!" Hannah whispered in my ear as we drove off into the Beverly 
Hills sunset. 
</P>
<P>
But what do you talk about with Dear Abby? Perhaps I should just turn to her 
and say what's on my mind: 
</P>
<P>
DEAR ABBY: My mother died before my daughter Hannah was born. She was such an 
indulgent grandma, always sending my older daughter, Emma, beautiful little 
dresses and toys, even if she couldn't afford them. I know it sounds 
irrational, but I keep dreaming she'll come back and do something special for 
Hannah. Am I nuts? 
</P>
<P>
FAIRY-TALE BELIEVER 
</P>
<P>
Abby had written to me. Not because I wrote to her, but out of the blue -- 
wonderful letters saying kind things about my column. I called and asked to 
take her to lunch, but she was busy churning out the six columns a week a 
working girl must do to pay the limo bill. Now, Hannah and I are her dinner 
guests. We follow her into an elegant French restaurant. I realize that Emma 
will kill me for this later. 
</P>
<P>
Rows of young waiters, like a Busby Berkeley chorus line, fall in with, "Good 
evening, Mrs. Phillips" and "Nice to see you, Abby." We are seated in her 
private dining room, which looks out over the dimly lit scene. "This way, we 
can still watch the couples smooching," she says. 
</P>
<P>
I'm reminded that she was no sob sister when she entered the old boys' world of 
journalism in the '50s. She made it on saucy one-liners, like her response to 
the reader who wrote, "What's the difference between a wife and a mistress?" 
"Night and day," Her Dearness responded. 
</P>
<P>
Perhaps others, besides her hairdresser, know the secret of how Abby, who 
turned 71 on the Fourth of July, still looks like a girl of 50. As she sits 
between Hannah and me, I note her blue-and-white silk dress and matching coat, 
her pearl-and-diamond necklace, her purple pumps and purple Chanel bag, and the 
perfect red nails on her tiny white hands. 
</P>
<P>
Hannah struggles to eat the huge filet mignon, even after she has brushed aside 
the yucky stuff called foie gras. I am enjoying my duck in raspberry sauce, 
which at 24 bucks a pop ain't chopped liver. I'm acquainted with Abby's 
biography because my older daughter had done a report last year on the famous 
Sioux City twins -- Abby and her sister, Esther Pauline (Eppie) Friedman 
Lederer, a.k.a. Ann Landers. 
</P>
<P>
I tell Abby that we have a few things in common besides the fact that her dad 
from Minsk and my dad from Pinsk came to Midwestern America and opened movie 
theaters. Like her, I didn't start writing a column until my late 30s and, like 
her, I began with the San Francisco Chronicle. 
</P>
<P>
"When I went to the Chronicle, I didn't even have a Social Security number," 
Abby says. "I said I'd gladly do it for free, but they insisted I be paid." 
</P>
<P>
I suggest, "They'd take it for free today." 
</P>
<P>
Every question I ask Abby turns out to be a cliche. "What did you think of 
Nathanael West's 'Miss Lonelyhearts'?" 
</P>
<P>
"Honey, everyone always asks me that." 
</P>
<P>
Hannah asks the questions nobody has ever asked before: "Are those real 
diamonds? . . . Is that really your chauffeur? . . . Are you friends with any 
movie stars that you like?" 
</P>
<P>
Singing waiters arrive bearing a special chocolate Charlotte cake with a candle 
in it for Hannah's "birthday," which was actually three months ago. It is just 
the kind of dramatic deed my mother would have done. 
</P>
<P>
Sated with cake, Hannah announces: "This is the fanciest restaurant I have ever 
been to. This is the longest dinner I have ever sat through." 
</P>
<P>
We leave. The coach awaits us. The chauffeur-cum-bodyguard takes us to Rodeo 
Drive and follows us as we stroll. Cameras roll as celebs and long-legged 
ladies enter a Leroy Neiman gallery opening. A few doors down, there's another 
bash for an artist whose oeuvre consists of paintings of Brooke Shields on 
motorcycles. A man gets out of his Rolls-Royce and says to us, "Three girls out 
on the town?" 
</P>
<P>
Abby takes Hannah's hand and leads her up Rodeo on a docent's tour through this 
big-ticket Disneyland. Then she kisses us good night and sends us to bed. 
</P>
<P>
Later, I tell Hannah, "I wish I hadn't had wine. It seemed like such a dream." 
</P>
<P>
"But it was like a dream to me too," she says. "Did you see her rings? We're 
talking big ones." 
</P>
<P>
Hannah may remember the sparkly things -- the chandelier in the restaurant and 
Abby's diamond earrings. But when I think back to that night in Beverly Hills, 
I'll remember Mama. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
