<HEADLINE>
<P>
SPECIAL FORMULAS TARGET PESTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Just when everything seems to be going along so well, those pesky garden pests 
show up and begin to consume the bountiful meal in your garden. 
</P>
<P>
You can usually control them in one of several ways: by physically removing 
them, by bringing in other insects that are their natural enemies or by using a 
packaged product containing active ingredients to kill the pest. 
</P>
<P>
Caterpillars, budworms and other critters can be handled very nicely by the use 
of one of the bacillus thuringiensis products. This is not a chemical; rather 
it is a bacteria which, when eaten by the unsuspecting worm, causes one last 
stomach ache. 
</P>
<P>
Ants are also having a field day now. Silica gel compound is a very safe 
product that is neither a chemical nor a germ. It causes an insect's feet to 
stick together -- so it also works on silverfish and other creepy crawlers. 
</P>
<P>
You can also find very finely ground products that will take care of all of 
these monsters as well as snails and slugs. Be sure to use any product 
according to the instructions on the label. 
</P>
<P>
Most products have a very short life span once exposed to the sun or air. 
Although it can limit the overall effectiveness of the product, they're made 
that way for our safety. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA071689-0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 82674 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 16, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Real Estate; Part 8; Page 12; Column 1; Real Estate Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
696 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PULL LIGHT INTO HOME FROM ABOVE; 
</P>
<P>
BETTER SKYLIGHTS MAKE INSTALLATION AND UPKEEP EASIER FOR HOMEOWNERS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By A. J. HAND, Distributed by the Los Angeles Times Syndicate. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Skylights: For the past 20 years or so, they have been one of the hottest 
"accessories" to be added to the home. And during that time, the reasons for 
adding them have gotten better and better. 
</P>
<P>
Not many years ago, skylights were "net energy wasters." What they gained in 
terms of free light and wintertime solar heating, they more than lost in terms 
of winter heat loss and unwanted summer heat gain. 
</P>
<P>
To solve that problem, the major makers formed a committee to discover ways to 
improve efficiency. What they found was that most energy loss was taking place 
through highly conductive metal skylight frames, and through air leaks. 
</P>
<P>
It didn't take them long to remedy that situation. Improved seals and gaskets 
were the answer to air leaks. To combat conductive losses through the frame, 
some makers switched from metal to vinyl or fiberglass. Others stayed with 
metal, but installed "thermal breaks," insulating barriers of plastic between 
inner and outer shells of the frame. 
</P>
<P>
With those improvements, skylights turned into net energy gainers. And with the 
introduction in the past few years of new energy-efficient glazing systems such 
as Low-E glass and Heat Mirror, energy performance has gone up another notch. 
</P>
<P>
Today, a good skylight can probably pay for itself in energy savings in 15 
years or less, including the price of installation. And some are so easy to 
install that you can do the job yourself, cutting pay-back time even further. 
</P>
<P>
If all this convinces you to put a skylight or two in your home, here are some 
tips and features to look for. 
</P>
<P>
SIZING: As a rule of thumb, a skylight should have an area roughly equal to 
1/23 the area of the room it will serve. If you want extra light -- perhaps for 
a plant room -- you should increase the size. You'll also need a bigger 
skylight if your ceilings are higher than the usual eight feet. 
</P>
<P>
GLAZING: Single- glazed skylights are OK in the West or other regions where the 
climate is mild. But even there, double glazing can help fight excessive heat 
gain. In colder climates, single glazing just doesn't make sense. Here you 
should consider, in order of increasing effectiveness, double glazing, Low-E 
glass, and Heat Mirror systems. What about plastic? There was a time when the 
plastic bubble ruled the roof. But over the years, glass has begun to take 
over, partly because of its flat, crisp look, and partly because of the 
efficiency of the new glass glazing systems. Double-glazed plastic still 
performs well, however, and if you live in the hail belt, plastic's impact 
resistance is a strong selling point. 
</P>
<P>
FEATURES: If you plan to try installing a skylight yourself, you'll want a 
self-curbing design with an easy installation system. Try to get ahold of the 
installation instructions for any skylight you are considering. If you don't 
like what you see, investigate another brand. Some makers such as Wasco 
actually encourage do-it-yourself installation. Others don't. 
</P>
<P>
VENTING OR FIXED? Skylights that open may cost 50% more than fixed types, but 
that can be money well spent in some cases. Located high in the ceiling, an 
open skylight does a good job of venting off hot, stuffy air. I have two 
skylights in my bedroom and opening them both can usually get me through a hot 
summer night without air conditioning. 
</P>
<P>
Some venting skylights are designed to open so you can clean them from inside 
the house, and this can be a boon if you live in an area with dusty or polluted 
air or heavy bird traffic. If your skylight will be located high in a cathedral 
ceiling, you might want to invest in a motorized opening system, controlled by 
a wall switch. I run my bedroom skylights by hand with a long extension crank. 
It's not particularly easy to handle. 
</P>
<P>
SHADES: At certain times of the day or year, a skylight can let in too much 
light. For those occasions, a shade is the answer. Most makers offer them as 
options. I put a light tan roll-up shade on the skylight in my dressing room. I 
still get lots of light, but I keep direct sun off the clothes in the open 
closets, and that helps prevent fading. If you want to block off light almost 
completely, a shade in a dark, opaque color will do the trick. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Marvin Windows' skylights bring natural light into work area of room, 
above. Single glide roof window in bathroom is easy to open for venting 
purposes, at right. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
